{"author":{"id":"b65f3d7cc6365cdda97889669465cb80d6eb6b487ba87271045738f4aaeb081b"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1629792084,"nonce":"jh7pNSbsM5YtQitK0MLWBh06Ls4=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDU6SXNzdWU5Nzc4MTkwNDE=","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/3896","origin":"github"},"title":"Diamond and the Blast database support","message":"Hi,\nsince 2.08 [Diamond ](https://github.com/bbuchfink/diamond/releases) is able to deal with already BlastP formatted files.\n\nWhat is the best way to handle this in the XML?\nFirst I thought that I could simply add the `blastdb_p.loc` file as a possible input. But the version 2.0.10 added the `prepdb` step:\n\n\u003e Using BLAST databases now requires a preprocessing step using the command prepdb. The command line is: diamond prepdb -d /path/to/database. This call runs quickly and will write some small auxiliary files into the database directory.\n\nSo? If I add `blastdb_p.loc` file as a possible input, I will have to deal with the `prepdb` step (not really a big deal), but Galaxy will then try to write something in the blastp index path, and this part is not really a good idea I think.\n\nI was thinking to create a dedicated path for the Diamond indexes (with symbolic links to the already BlastP formatted files as we have a lot of them). And within this path, we can pre-launch the `prepdb` step. So Galaxy would be able to use these enhanced BlastP indexes.\n\nWhat do you think about that?","files":null}]}